conjecture(kepler): no sphere packing beats the face-centred cubic density

Johannes Kepler asserts that no arrangement of equal spheres fills space more
densely than the pyramidal stacking used for cannonballs, a density of pi over
the square root of eighteen.

Status: math.conjectured
---
proof(hsiang): a claimed proof by spherical trigonometry

Wu-Yi Hsiang announces a proof reducing the problem to inequalities in spherical
geometry, worked out by hand.

Status: math.proved-informal
Closes: conjecture:kepler
---
refute(hsiang)!: key cases are asserted without justification

Hales and others show that several of the hardest configurations are dismissed
without a complete argument, so the reduction does not go through.

Status: math.disproved
Disproves: hsiang
BREAKING CHANGE: Hsiang's proof is not accepted; the conjecture is open again.
---
axiomatize~(tame-graphs): the finite list of tame plane graphs

Every potential counterexample maps to one of a finite set of "tame" planar
graphs. The enumeration was produced and checked by computer.

Status: math.axiomatised
AXIOM: tame-graphs (a 1998 computer enumeration, not independently audited)
Cites: Hales 2005, Annals of Mathematics
---
axiomatize~(lp-bounds): linear-programming bounds rule out each case

For every tame graph, a linear program bounds the local density below the
threshold. Roughly a hundred thousand programs, all solved by computer.

Status: math.axiomatised
AXIOM: lp-bounds (a 1998 computer search, not independently audited)
Cites: Hales 2005, Annals of Mathematics
---
proof(hales): the Kepler conjecture, modulo the computer searches

A densest packing would force a tame graph that the linear programs exclude. The
argument is sound; its trusted base is the two computer searches.

Status: math.axiomatised
Assumes: tame-graphs
Assumes: lp-bounds
Closes: conjecture:kepler
---
formalize(tame-graphs): the tame classification, checked in Isabelle

The enumeration of tame graphs is reproduced and verified by the Isabelle kernel,
removing the trust in the original program.

Formal-Statement: isabelle:Kepler.tame_classification
Status: math.machine-checked
Verified-By: Isabelle
Proves: tame-graphs
---
formalize(lp-bounds): the bounds, checked in HOL Light

Every linear-programming bound is re-derived inside HOL Light, so the kernel,
not an external solver, certifies each case.

Formal-Statement: isabelle:Kepler.lp_bounds
Status: math.machine-checked
Verified-By: HOL Light
Proves: lp-bounds
---
formalize(kepler): a fully machine-checked Kepler conjecture

With both searches kernel-checked, the Flyspeck project closes the proof with no
unaudited program left.

Formal-Statement: isabelle:Kepler.kepler_conjecture
Status: math.machine-checked
Verified-By: HOL Light and Isabelle
Depends-On: Kepler.tame_classification
Depends-On: Kepler.lp_bounds
Supersedes: hales
Closes: conjecture:kepler
Cites: Hales et al. 2017, Forum of Mathematics Pi
